<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com â€“ The U.S. dollar was down against all of the major currencies on Tuesday, amid rising market sentiment and after the U.S. posted a larger-than-expected trade deficit in May.During European afternoon trade, the greenback was down against the euro, with EUR/USD gaining 0.58% to hit 1.2670. Earlier in the day, Greece's Public Debt Management Agency sold EUR 1.625 billion of 6-month Treasury bills, its first debt auction since receiving an EU/IMF emergency loan package in May, easing fears over the country's ability to borrow on financial markets.The greenback was also down against the pound and the yen, with GBP/USD surging 0.86% to hit 1.5160, and USD/JPY shedding 0.26% to hit 88.39.Earlier in the day, Britain's Office for National Statistics said the rate of consumer price inflation was 3.2% in June, after advancing 3.4% in May.The decline was in line with expectations and was above the Bank of England's targeted rate of inflation of 2%.The greenback was also down against the Swiss franc, with USD/CHF tumbling 0.70% to hit 1.0533.Earlier Tuesday, the Swiss Federal Statistics Office said the producer and import price index fell 0.4% in June, after advancing 0.3% in May.Analysts had expected the index to advance 0.2% in June.The greenback was also down against its Australian, New Zealand and Canadian counterparts, with AUD/USD advancing 0.36% to hit 0.8789, NZD/USD climbing 0.66% to hit 0.7164 and USD/CAD shedding 0.60% to hit 1.0310. The dollar index, which tracks the performance of the greenback versus a basket of six other major currencies, was down 0.59%.             ]]></raw>
